At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements into a civil war-consumed Iraq as “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its aftermath.”
The following months, however, showed that Bush’s strategy, which issued recommendations from campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to succeed to the point that the newspapers at present do not talk at all about Iraq.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, that is, objectively speaking, he left his successor in a much more favorable final situation than one could hope for.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again the campaign commanders who asked him to increase the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the White House's reluctances despite subordination habits.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months, but in the absence of a better option, he cheated at least the general of 10,000 soldiers.
It succeeded in removing the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though it originally counted on 10,000.
What is causing the most problems in the entire Obama strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete this whole process within three years. All of Obama's doctrine brings more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that a halving of the increase will bear the same fruit as the increase in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The Afghan situation is the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaty is respected.
In these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing their leadership from day to day according to their arrangement.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain only powder in the eyes behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is particularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity on relations, which are further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the founding of a "prompt state to act", which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy makes him perplexed by his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only worsened and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic heart and out of reality can be convinced that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war for their "quick return home" will bring there a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will regard it as the indirect confession of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that Europeans’ willingness to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is turning negatively.
European politicians do not know or want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the mountains of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and if the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves faced with the very difficult question of a solution to the problem by the use of military force.
We will have to respond, for example, at a time when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
Any solution of this kind will, however, lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
The only ruse for Obama is that he has three years left until the presidential election and therefore there is still enough time for him to embark on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
