Defense Secretary Robert Gates said on Friday that the world’s major powers would soon impose “significant additional sanctions” on Iran because of its inability to engage in talks on nuclear ambitions.
Gates, speaking in front of a barracks of 300 U.S. troops in northern Iraq during a week-long visit to war zones in Afghanistan and Iraq, de-dramatized the possibility of military action against the Islamic Republic.
There is no good option in Iran, he said, in response to a soldier’s question about the possibility of such an outcome.
One of the things that weighs on me the most is that if I’ve learned one thing in Iraq in the last six years, it’s the unpredictable side inherent in the war.
The Obama administration considers a set of sanctions that would target Iran’s military and political elite, but Gates pointed out that some of these sanctions could also affect Iranians on the street.
He said a “set of motivations and punishments” might be needed to persuade the Iranian government that it would in fact be less safe with nuclear weapons “because its people would suffer enormously” from these sanctions.
On Friday, in a statement by White House spokesman Robert Gibbs, the administration joined European leaders in a warning that Iran will face "probable" consequences if it does not bring its nuclear program back into full compliance with the UN Security Council and its monitoring body, the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA).
Iran persists in saying that it wants to develop its nuclear experimentation solely for a peaceful purpose.
In the talks in Geneva on October 1, he said he would resume the dialogue on reducing his nuclear program and agreed to abandon a significant part of his enriched uranium storage, in exchange for fuel desperately needed for a medical research reactor.
The administration has pushed for such an agreement, a means of building trust on both sides and saving time for negotiations.
Since then, Iran appears to have distanced itself from attempts at a deal - in part, experts say, because Iran's leadership is divided over whether or not to engage with the United States.
Frankly, in my opinion, Iran’s stiffening of some of the international community’s proposals that they had actually agreed to in early October has prompted the international community, including Russians and Chinese, to join on what they had not envisaged, in terms of significant additional sanctions against the Iranians, Gates said.
President Obama set December 31 as a deadline for Iran to respond to the proposals, before turning to other options, including pursuing what Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton once called “increased sanctions.”
In a statement Thursday in New York, Iran's mission to the United Nations denounced what it calls "unfounded allegations" by some members of the Security Council about Iran's nuclear activities and said it agreed to continue talks with the United States and five other major world powers, "with a view to achieving a long-term solution."
Gates, who was due to return to Washington late Friday, met with Iraqi Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki in the morning before taking the plane to the rich Kurdish oil region to meet with troop leaders in Kirkuk, Kurdish and Irbil.
Tensions persist between the Kurds and the Arab majority in Iraq, particularly regarding borders, property rights and income sharing.
Gates urged both sides to reduce the potential conflict in order to avoid any delays in U.S. plans to reduce the number of U.S. troops from 115,000 to 50,000 by the end of August.
U.S. officials quoted Gates as saying to Massoud Barzani, President of the Kurdistan Regional Government: "We will preserve your security, your prosperity and your autonomy within a unified Iraq."
We will not abandon you.”
In aging China, a change of direction
Wang Weijia and her husband grew up surrounded by propaganda posters telling them, "Mother Earth is too tired to accommodate more children" and "An extra baby is an extra grave".
They learned the lesson so well that the Shanghai government authorities, alarmed by their city's insufficient birth rate and the ageing population, radically changed direction this summer and began encouraging young couples to have more than one child; their reaction was instantaneous and firm: never.
We have already given all our time and energy to one child.
We don’t have a second left,” said Wang, 31, a human resources director who has an 8-month-old son.
More than 30 years after the introduction of the one-child policy in China, creating two generations of unique children notoriously with good cheeks and spoiled, nicknamed the "little emperors", a population crisis threatens the country.
According to the UN, the average birth rate fell by 1.8 children per couple compared to six when the policy was implemented.
Population distribution, while the number of residents aged 60 and over is projected to explode, from 16.7 percent of the population in 2020 to 31.1 percent in 2050, is well above the global average of about 20 percent.
This imbalance is even worse in rich coastal cities with a highly educated population, such as Shanghai.
Last year, people aged 60 and over accounted for nearly 22 percent of the population of registered residents in Shanghai, while the birth rate was less than one child per couple.
Xie Lingli, Director of the Shanghai Municipal Population and Family Planning Commission, said that fertile couples should have babies in order to “help reduce the proportion of the aging population and prevent labor shortages in the future.”
Shanghai is about to become "as old - but not as rich, however - as developed countries such as Japan and Sweden," she said.
Progressive attenuation
Written in the country’s constitution in 1978, China’s one-child policy is undoubtedly the most controversial obligation introduced by the communist government to date.
Couples who violate this policy are likely to pay colossal fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and face discrimination in the workplace.
The Chinese authorities attributed to the police the duty to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers denounced abuses in the implementation of this policy.
In rural areas, some government officials have forced pregnant women with a second child to abort.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to an abnormally high male-to-female ratio.
In recent years, the authorities responsible for the population have gradually softened their position on the policy of the one child.
In 2004, they granted more exceptions to the rule -- including for city residents, members of ethnic minorities and cases where men and women are already unique children -- and in 2007, they softened many of their harsh slogans.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing, said central government authorities have recently discussed even more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children if one of the partners is a single child.
In July, Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to encourage births.
In no time, posters encouraging families to have only one child were replaced with copies of regulations detailing who has the right to have a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city’s government has dispatched family planning officials and volunteers to meet couples at their home and drag prospectuses under their door.
He also promised to provide psychological and financial advice to those who would like to have more than one child.
According to the head of family planning, the response was disappointing.
Disappointing response
Although officials in a rural suburban city of Shanghai say they have seen an increase in requests for files from couples wanting a second child after the campaign's launch, the more urban district reported that there was no change.
The municipality of Huinan, with a population of 115,000, for example, still receives only four to five applications per month.
Shanghai officials, disappointed, say that despite the campaign, the number of births in the city in 2010 is still projected to be only about 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009 but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the family planning committee in Shanghai’s Caolu municipality, said financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don’t want to have more children.
They want to provide for their first child, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said they would love to have two children and that they are legally allowed there.
But like many Chinese, they only have the minimum health insurance and life insurance given by the government.
Without social protection, they say, the decision would be irresponsible.
Westerners mistakenly consider the one-child policy a rights issue, said Yang, a construction engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with the couple's first child.
It's true, we're being robbed of the chance to have more than one child.
But the problem is not only the law.
It's the money.
Other couples cite psychological reasons to explain their hesitation.
Wang, Human Resources Manager, said she wanted only one child because she was one of herself. "We were the center of the family and we used to have everyone taking care of us."
We’re not used to taking care of someone else and we really don’t want to take care of others.”
Chen Zijian, 42 years old and owner of a translation company says it more strongly.
For middle-class couples working in pairs, who lower the birth rate, he says, one must be selfish, perhaps succeed.
People in their 20s or 30s grew up watching their parents fight in the early days of capitalist China and don’t want to have that lifestyle themselves, he says.
Even a single child needs a lot of time from his parents, he says.
A mother must give up at least two years of her social life.
Then there are the space problems -- "You need to change your apartment" -- and the planning -- "When your child is only 9 months old, you need to write his CV to get a place in the best kindergarten."
Most of his friends are ready for this experience once, Chen says, but not two.
Our generation is the first to benefit from a higher standard of living, he says.
We don’t want to make too many sacrifices.
The United Nations Group has draft plans for emission reductions
The U.N.-sponsored climate conference -- hitherto characterized by disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- returned to the limelight on Friday, following the publication of a document highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with most industrialized nations supporting it.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining hurdles, as much as it illuminated the way forward.
But it has been seen as a major breakthrough in time-consuming negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Written by a UN task force, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, both in the long term and in the long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed economies and new emerging economies could reduce their carbon production and what would be the upper limit of global temperature rise that policymakers would be willing to tolerate.
It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington, D.C., of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN Executive Secretary-General Yvo de Boer described as the “full picture.”
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 per cent in 2020 compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries, during the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 per cent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched negotiations on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impacts of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which dominated the negotiations since last week.
Mr. Todd Stern, U.S. Representative for Climate Negotiations, has rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared to voluntary efforts by major emerging economies, if they were not financed by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is becoming tougher on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text does not insist enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after China’s deputy foreign minister, He Yafei, said the U.S. chief negotiator either lacked “good sense” or was “extremely irresponsible” for saying earlier in the week that the U.S. would not financially help China to fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the Third World and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States arguing over their respective obligations while the poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that major powers are struggling to know who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries had become more aggressive in their attempt to hold major emitters accountable for their actions.
It’s really a game in which a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who is also Climate Adviser for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries that are more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they would continue to put pressure on Copenhagen to obtain a legally binding treaty, although most of the main participants say the negotiations will lead to a political agreement at the minimum.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission’s climate unit, said the action of the small island states “put political pressure on the full political process,” partly by what they are now unified and that they call on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
Debates became an urgent matter, as delegates focused on resolving most of the outstanding issues before the heads of government reached an agreement.
Senior officials such as the Indian Minister of the Environment, Jairam Ramesh and the Chinese Deputy Minister stepped off their plane and rushed to the Bella Center building to attend in-house meetings and information conferences, in order to be able to make claims that will be considered over the next week.
The real picture of the rally -- where 13,000 people come in and out of the Congress Palace every day -- guitar-playing activists perform nighttime shows mocking countries they believe are betraying each other, and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and no later than Wednesday, 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the court of the greats, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global conservation policy at Conservation International.
The heavy trucks are coming.
