Management revolution or end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of the big French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain.
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees, recalls the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about getting employees to adhere to determined "values" from above as it used to be, to impose on consumers products thought by them.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering markets in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from customer preference factors returns regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, moreover, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the IE "requires all stakeholders ... a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires commitment from employees that authoritarian management revenues are totally contrary.
That is why we call for a management revolution that would involve putting employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion polls – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incentivize this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- Firstly, because I have been able to see that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally arrives, after many detours, to do priority... what it has always done!
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from the great schools of engineers, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, out of intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leverages" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr strengthens leaders in a mechanistic governance posture, unsuitable for today's world.
Identifying and Measuring Mobilization Factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises requires adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in incorporating, in any reasoning or governance practice, a fundamental finding: for employees, engagement for the company is possible only if it clearly appears as a way to realize some of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life plans.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and put their human resource management “on the right track”.
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
