The Cradle of Dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae was similar to other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long by 1.50m tall, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with scissor claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues report in Thursday’s Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to feature these morphological features.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico which at the time was part of the emerging lands of the supercontinent, the Pangaea and was located towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the kinship links, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
In 2006, Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique to a Triassic sedimentary layer.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
Excavations have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
Researchers named it after Tawa after the Indian word Hopi for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and are limited to a few fragments of incomplete bones.
Not all paleontology experts share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he points out that it confirms some theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
However, most of the oldest fossils are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the earliest dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the Saurians were divided into three major groups of evolution: the theropods (carnivores)which include the tyrannosaur and the velociraptor that appeared later and from which descend the birds, the sauropods, quadrupeds with a long neck, and those which make up the triangular part of the ori.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the first theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues suggesting that the Tawa hallae possessed small air sacs in its bones at the skull level, as did birds that are descended from theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
Since the related lineage of the immense sauropods also possessed airbags and a light skeleton, it can be assumed that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the Saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three major lines of evolution split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e. the whole of the emerging lands that formed the supercontinent Pangaea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who would have migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of the journal Science Studies says there have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the Silesaurus, that lived in present-day Poland and that belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a wrong view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while virtually none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs became the dominant tetrapods of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch remains a mystery today.
At the time of the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of modern crocodiles and many other Saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread throughout the planet, thus fostering the development of many new species, while others, related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and Jurassic.
Such a success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction that the dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles would have disappeared.
Or else, the dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a favored meteorite unfolded a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and that since then had been vegetating in the shadows: they were mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are those of professors at the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley in California.
There are those of lecturers from the University of Naples, Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
