A conscious state of awakening, taking the form of a dream, can present itself in the most diverse forms, at best it is called visions, at worst it is madness.
But even though the trigger and effect differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiments of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, the second states of the shamans, psychoses and hallucinations are attributable to very similar processes.
There are hallucinations or delusions when the balance of neurotransmitter substances in the brain - primarily dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and achetylcholine - is broken and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disrupted.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts very often manifest during a schizophrenic psychosis.
The force of earthly attraction no longer has power over the person.
Since ancient times, philosophers and doctors have always looked at the relationship between madness and dreaming.
For Aristotle, hallucinations were a form of dream-awakened; Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, observed in 1861 "a great similarity between madness and dream", for Sigmund Freud the dream was even "a psychosis with all the irregularities, imaginations, delusions and sensory illusions that compose it".
It’s autumn 2001 when Henning T turns into a comic book character.
His body is in two dimensions with bright colors.
The earthly attraction no longer has power over him, he flies at the raz of the ceiling.
He feels a blow.
Behind him are winged, grimaceful devil creatures, bloody mouth, showing teeth.
They chase him, kick him with heavy flaming boots, throw him against the walls, he feels pain all over his body.
Toning voices, mean, screaming, coming out of the walls and the radio.
He can no longer stand those voices that insult and humiliate him.
Henning T. pulls two cables from his stereo, making it a loop and attaching it to a hook attached to the ceiling.
He climbs on a baffle and passes the loop around his neck.
He's jumping.
The loop detaches.
Let it be a lesson to you, shout the voices in a choir to rip out his eardrum. "Go to a clinic and get cured!"
Today Henning T. is 40 years old, he has experienced six acute psychoses, the last date of 2 years, the first of almost 20 years.
It was triggered by LSD.
The diagnosis: schizo-affective psychosis, paranoid, in addition it is manic-depressive, it takes drugs against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
During the psychosis I experienced terrible fears and deep despair.
Illusions are a cruel reality.
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their life; in psychiatric clinics it is the most common disease after depression.
In a schizophrenic crisis, the people involved can no longer make the difference between the inner world and the outer world, they find themselves in a state of hyper-excitement, which causes them to suffer from hallucinations, megalomania, relational madness or persecution.
It is very common to hear voices – voices that command, comment, or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The person concerned can no longer distinguish between the important and the insignificant, the brain can no longer filter the disruptive signals, the consciousness is drowned under the sensations.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the door to a tide of ideas and fantasies from the deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, according to Professor Thomas Fuchs, head of the department of psychiatry at the Heidelberg University Hospital (Allgemeine Psychiatrie im Universitätsklinikum).
The schizophrenic is in the middle of the situation, all with a meaning centered on him.
At the same time he finds himself in a passive role, he is like in a dream, overcome by events and can not act on them actively.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, manipulated.
In general they do not have the opportunity to adjust reality, illusions are a cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Experience once in your life a hallucination.
Unlike the dream, according to Fuchs, “the sensory and spatial structure of reality that is perceived during psychosis is fundamentally preserved.”
Delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in a real setting.
Why our brains make these kinds of convertibles is always a riddle for researchers.
Exceptional situations can cause everyone to temporarily lose their perception of reality, according to Fuchs.
But only a small number of people will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies on twins have shown that genes are not the only determinants.
The researchers assume that the individuals involved have minor brain damage.
It is assumed that the neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development, for example by a viral infection of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But what remains unexplained is the way in which the abnormality of the neuronal system occurs and the fact that it does not manifest itself for many years.
Environmental factors also play a role – stress or a traumatic experience can be a trigger for psychosis, if, however, there is a predisposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can trigger psychoses because they act on neurotransmitters.
When our brains heat up.
What is crazy, says psychology professor Erich Kasten from Lübeck, is that psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them while others buy very expensive drugs to get rid of them.
The pleasant or unpleasant perception of illusions is often just a matter of perspective.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and illusory image phenomena for ten years: last year he published his results in a book entitled "The unreal world in our heads".
Hallucinations are part of the concomitant phenomena typical of psychoses, but also of an impressive number of other pathologies.
Among them are mental disorders such as borderline or depression but also migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease or cranial trauma.
It is surprising to find that under certain conditions even the brains of healthy people are prone to hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of fragments of memories that are normally inhibited.
They take shape when the areas of the brain that deal with sensory perceptions are hyperactive or not sufficiently restrained; when our brains heat up but also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just like a brain injury or psychosis.
But also the lack of stimuli, stress, sorrows of love or other exceptional mental states.
In recent studies, one-third of participants admit to having hallucinated at least once in their life.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and goes to high school.
A young girl doing everything normal, to be honest.
If only there were no pictures and voices.
During the recreation, it happens that a young boy, thin, with long chestnut hair, speaks to him.
When she responds, her comrades look at her, astonished – no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think this shy girl is a lunatic dreamer but Sarah K does not dream, she is sure of it.
She is awake, hears and sees this boy just as she sees and hears the girl sitting next to her on the bench.
It can even perceive its presence momentarily.
It's a nice feeling, she finds this young man friendly.
Am I crazy? she asks sometimes.
But she knows well that this young man and the other visions are not real and that they will disappear again.
At night the apparitions are generally frightening.
Visions are often heavy.
When she is in class, she may not be able to attend the class because the teacher is just presenting a new student in her eyes and ears while he is invisible to others and the teacher is visibly explaining equations to the table.
At night the apparitions are generally frightening.
When, in the darkness of her bedroom, she waits for the sleep that comes too rarely and far too late, she can often not make the distinction if she is awake or already dreaming, if the images she sees, the grim faces or the girl with bloody incisions on her arms and legs are in front of her eyes open or iron.
Leave me alone, she yells at these creatures.
She doesn't talk about it to her parents or friends, they would take her for a fool.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She got her bachelor's degree last year and she lives with her friend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she came into contact via the internet with psychologist Kasten she knows very well that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art of despair.
When someone is socially isolated or does not have enough stimulation, the chances are high that they will have hallucinations after a while.
I guess the brain isn't busy enough, so there's animation.
Sarah K., the only daughter, was afraid of other children when she was little and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13, that the man she called dad, since she was of the age of thinking, was not her real father.
These are the same brain areas that are active for visual and acoustic hallucinations, and for real impressions and sounds, so it is very difficult for people like Sarah K to differentiate between illusion and reality. "Every experience," according to Kasten "is held in the brain, reality is formed from there.
Hallucinations are also images that form in the brain, which is why they seem so real.”
For Kasten, nocturnal dreams are also a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, the mentally healthy person is able to recognize that fantasies are not real images.
That’s why Kasten advises his patients to cherish hallucinations as a particular talent.
There is only one step between dreaming and hallucination.
In our world too focused on consciousness, we unfortunately quickly tend to take imaginary experiments for pathologies, according to Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the clinic for psychiatry and psychotherapy at Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful disease but also contains something positive, creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the form of the so-called onyroid experience, a particular form of the dream-awakened modification of consciousness.
Onyroid experiences are very complex semi-dreams that are perceived as real by the one who lives them and that he cannot differentiate from the dream even when he is awake.
The onyroid state of consciousness manifests itself during trauma or in situations of extreme pathologies such as for patients with polyradiculopathy who are fully conscious, experience motor paralysis.
According to Schmidt-Degenhard, when a human being is threatened by a loss of self and the world, due to a total and lasting inability to move, he replaces this real situation that affects his life, by his own imaginary world that is separated from reality.
It is a state of mental limit between dreaming and hallucination.
As it is not possible to overcome the situation in reality, a change of world takes place but the real situation is represented in the imagination.
It is, in fact, an intense form of means and interpretation, in an intolerable situation in itself, a capacity of organization that is given to us men, so as not to sink into nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real even later in the memories.
Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Classen also describes his onychoid experiences in his book "Changing the Heart" as a saving action for the soul.
He is 49 years old, at the time when his consciousness leaves for a trip of several days after the operation of a heart valve followed by a transplant; during this time, his body is condemned to remain immobile in resuscitation.
Claussen dives into a world he has created from scratch, visiting foreign places, traveling through time . He sees himself as an old man alone in a railway sanatorium, a robot at his bedside watching over his health.
He lives in the Middle Ages among nobles who make blood-based narcotics.
He is kidnapped by a Greek motorcycle who takes him to his country, surfs with his hospital bed in the snowy Alps and meets a Korean mobster.
It is completely absorbed in this imaginary world, everything is real even later in its memories.
According to Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
The dream is a completely different state, he writes, describing what he has experienced.
Unlike dreams, memories from mental journeys are extremely clear and very detailed even years later.
It can even be said that they are much more distinct and more intense than actual experience.
The intensity of this experience makes the horizon of our other daily experiences burst, according to psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, onyroid delusions, psychoses, hallucinations and psychedelic experiences show us how fragile our inner representations of external reality are even in a state of wakefulness.
Any change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten "may cause a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be quite rewarding.
